[Patient] How much water should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for 8-10 glasses of water a day, but consult your doctor for personalized advice.
[Patient] Is it okay to drink other fluids like juice or soda?
[Educator] Water is best, but limit sugary drinks. Consider herbal tea or infused water for variety.
[Patient] How can I tell if I'm retaining too much fluid?
[Educator] Watch for sudden weight gain, swelling in legs, or shortness of breath. Report any changes.
[Patient] Can I have salty foods if I drink more water?
[Educator] Limit salt intake to reduce fluid retention. Try herbs and spices for flavor instead.
[Patient] Should I avoid all fluids before bedtime?
[Educator] Limiting fluids before bed can reduce nighttime bathroom trips. Spread intake evenly throughout the day.
[Patient] Can I have coffee or tea in moderation?
[Educator] Caffeine can affect fluid balance. Limit to 1-2 cups a day and monitor hydration.
[Patient] How do I track my daily fluid intake?
[Educator] Use a water bottle with measurements or a hydration app to track intake easily.
[Patient] Should I be concerned if my urine is dark yellow?
[Educator] Dark urine can indicate dehydration. Aim for pale yellow urine to stay hydrated.
[Patient] How can I stay motivated to drink enough water every day?
[Educator] Set reminders on your phone, use a water bottle you like, and involve family in tracking.